<br>
I met my friends and soon-to-be guildmates there.  A motley collection of folks that couldn't understand each other, but recognized the quality of the player behind the character.  In time, we learned one another's habits, and grew into the dismal little fighting unit we are today. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
But it's always been more about the experience to me, instead of the reward I would get, and the experiences I had in the first, say, 20 levels of my time here were all great.  When one is forced to travel through dangerous territories, without the aid of high-level help or instantaneous, totally safe travel, one has an opportunity to develop a relationship with their fellow players.  Much moreso than today's world of /lfg tool, everyone can learn every language in a heartbeat, lack of alignment restrictions, and all the other things that made this server interesting when it started. <br>
<br>
I stay here because my guild and my friends are here, and this is likely still the best server in EQ, but it's a far damn way off from the way it started out, and probably not much different from the server I abandoned five characters on. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://itsinhere.com/saga/Elsbetsig.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> <br>
