<br>
I played EQ when it first came out. Started a Karana ranger that was born in a little place called Surefall glade. I remember hunting gnolls in blackburrow and making the mad dash accross Karana to get to Freeport for smithing supplies (only place they were sold back in the day). When I got accross (took me about 40minutes to make the whole run if I remember correctly w/o SoW) Once I got to Freeport, I'd purcahse some sharpening stones, put all my gear in the bank, and use the good old fashion ranger gate <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> . Theres a well fed shark just by the docks in freeport. hehe. People use to make tons of money standing at the Qeynos forge sharpening rusty weapons for people (well tons of money at the time) because a sharpened rusty was the best a newb could really expect to get. <br>
<br>
I remember my first trip to Faydwer. The zones were so much different then my homeland of Qeynos Hills. The flat rolling planes were replaced with rolling hills. I spent some time in crushbone, and eventually found my way to Unrest. Exploration is what tied me to the game. The sense of distance was a very nice feature...however...<br>
<br>
I remember dying on a &quot;just one more pull&quot; and having to stay up an extra 2 hours late at night because I had forgot to bind by soul accross the oot. My group had to log and I ended up CRing myself. I remember not being able to group with friends because I only had 2 hours to play and by the time we got to each other I'd have to log. I remember having to plan a couple days in advance if I wanted to go to a dungeon simply so I could get my character to that part of the world. I remember camping Rubicite in Cazic thule because it was the ONLY upgrade for Rangers/Shaman/Rogues.<br>
<br>
The new expansions have given us one of the richest online fantasy realms today. Some people choose to ignore parts of i, and really thats their perogative. The expansions have worked hard to counter some of the problems they've had by making travel easier, introduce a larger variety of loot so there is not a set &quot;loot progression&quot; that everyone has to go through, and by giving us more places to explore. EQ is definitely a different game today then it was when it was first released, but I would argue in many ways its better.<br>
<br>
The pivotal aspect of EQ that makes it horrid or fun is the people that play it. I quit right before Kunark came out because I just couldn't stand the people anymore. I decided to try again on FV right before Luclin. The people here never cease to amaze me. Yes, we have our share of asshats and d00dz but there is no way to avoid that. FV is still the best server around. <br>
<br>
Additionally, I believe in the PS2 version of EQ, and planned for EQ2, they are going to use a different method to control travel. I really like this idea and I think it goes a long way to address some of the problems with community and distance that you mentioned. In EQOA and EQ2, I believe you have to travel everywhere on foot once. In EQOA, once you have been to a city, you can pruchase a &quot;carriage ride&quot; to it from any other city. I think this method makes it so people actually have to explore the world once, but after the excitement of crossing the neverending Karanas has faded (trust me it fades pretty fast after the 10th time) you can just catch a quick ride there. <br>
<br>
On insta-death....all I have to say is...how many times have you died because you did something stupid? How lame would it be to make it to level 40 only to acidently run off a cliff to your death? Or hit autoattack on a NPC...<br>
<br>
Not that I've ever done these things mind you...<br>
<br>
Oh..and forget that you don't have an eb item...<br>
<br>
<br>
